The '''Nonhuman Turn'''<ref name="GrusinGrusin2015">{{cite book|author1=Richard Grusin|author2=Richard A. Grusin|title=The Nonhuman Turn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sxzOoQEACAAJ|year=2015|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|isbn=978-0-8166-9466-2}}</ref> describes a late 20th and 21st Century movement within the arts, humanities and social sciences, as practitioners of these disciplines turn away from the [[Social constructivism|Social Constructivism]] of the earlier 20th Century, in favour of emergent philosophies which seek to decenter the human, and to emphasize instead the agency of the [[Non-human|nonhuman]] world.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Nonhuman Turn|last=Grusin|first=Richard|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|year=2015|isbn=978-0-8166-9466-2|editor-last=Grusin|editor-first=Richard|location=Minneapolis, MN|chapter=Introduction|quote=|via=}}</ref> The phrase is adopted by Richard Grusin in his introduction to a collection of essays of the same name, based on the proceedings of the 2012 conference on the Nonhuman Turn, hosted by the [[Center for 21st Century Studies]] at the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.<ref name=":0" />
== Constituent Philosophies == The nonhuman turn is not been a homogenous movement. Instead it should be thought of as an umbrella term covering a number of developments in philosophy and critical theory across a range of disciplines. The key constituents of this wider movement include: * [[Animal studies]]<ref name="KeetleyTenga2016">{{cite book|author1=Dawn Keetley|author2=Angela Tenga|title=Plant Horror: Approaches to the Monstrous Vegetal in Fiction and Film|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AvzFDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-137-57063-5|pages=18}}</ref> * [[New materialism]] * [[Object-oriented ontology]]
